Introduction

With this script, I explored the data files with English texts for the capstone project. For these exploratory text analyses, I mainly used the package quanteda. I assessed the document characteristics, word frequencies and ngram frequencies.

Data loading

data <- readtext("texts/*.txt",
                   docvarsfrom = "filenames", 
                   docvarnames = c("lang", "type"),
                   dvsep = "-", 
                   encoding = "utf-8")

Summary of documents

path <- getwd()
blog <- readLines(file.path(path, 'texts', data$doc_id[1]), skipNul = TRUE)
news <- readLines(file.path(path, 'texts', data$doc_id[2]), skipNul = TRUE)
twitter <- readLines(file.path(path, 'texts', data$doc_id[3]), skipNul = TRUE)

res <- c()
size <- cbind(file.size(file.path(path, 'texts', data$doc_id[1]))/2^20, 
              file.size(file.path(path, 'texts', data$doc_id[2]))/2^20, 
              file.size(file.path(path, 'texts', data$doc_id[3]))/2^20)
chars <- cbind(sum(nchar(blog)), sum(nchar(news)), sum(nchar(twitter)))
words <- cbind(wordcount(blog), wordcount(news), wordcount(twitter))
lines <- cbind(length(blog), length(news), length(twitter))
res <- rbind(size, chars, words, lines)
rownames(res) <- c("File size", "Characters", "Words", "Lines")
colnames(res) <- c("Blogs", "News", "Twitter")

t <- kableExtra::kable(res)
kableExtra::kable_styling(t)

Making corpus of documents and sampling

corp <- corpus(data)
corpsentc <- corpus_reshape(corp, to=c("sentences"), use_docvars = TRUE)
corps <- corpus_sample(corpsentc, size = 3000, replace = FALSE, by = "document")
corps2 <- corpus_reshape(corps, to = "documents")

dtm <- dfm(corps2, tolower=TRUE, stem=FALSE, remove=stopwords('en'), remove_punct=TRUE,
           remove_numbers = TRUE, remove_symbols = TRUE)
dtm <- dfm_trim(dtm, min_termfreq = 10)

Word frequencies

These are the word frequencies without the stopwords.

textplot_wordcloud(dtm, max_words = 100, color=pal_material("blue")(10))   ## top 100 (most frequent) words

textplot_wordcloud(dtm, max_words = 150, comparison = TRUE, color=pal_startrek()(3)) ## top 150 ordered per document type

Keyness Twitter vs News

type_corp <- corpus_subset(corps2, 
                             type %in% c("twitter", "news"))
typedfm <- dfm(type_corp, groups = "type", tolower=TRUE, stem=FALSE, remove=stopwords('en'), remove_punct=TRUE,
               remove_numbers = TRUE, remove_symbols = TRUE)
result_keyness <- textstat_keyness(typedfm, target = "twitter")
textplot_keyness(result_keyness, color=c("steelblue", "grey"))

Tokenizing

toks <- tokens(corps2, remove_punct=TRUE, remove_numbers = TRUE, remove_symbols = TRUE)
ntoken(toks)
##   en_US-blogs.txt    en_US-news.txt en_US-twitter.txt 
##             53991             53822             34890

Frequencies of 2 grams

toks_ngram <- tokens_ngrams(toks, n = 2)
dfngram <- dfm(toks_ngram)
tstat_freq <- textstat_frequency(dfngram)

tstat_freq %>% 
    mutate(rel_freq = frequency/sum(frequency)*100) %>% 
    arrange(rel_freq) %>% 
    top_n(20) %>% 
    ggplot(aes(x = reorder(feature, rel_freq), y = rel_freq)) +
    geom_point(color=pal_nejm()(1)) +
    coord_flip() +
    labs(x = NULL, y = "Frequency") +
    theme_minimal() +
    ggtitle("2-gram frequencies")
## Selecting by rel_freq

## Plans for modelling For the modelling, I plan to use the tables with the ngram frequencies. Depending on the number of words of the input, the script will look up a matching ngram with the highest frequency to predict the next word. For an input of 1 word, the bigram table can be used, for 2 word inputs, the 3-gram table, etcetera.
